h the issues that are fundamental to our understanding of diet and food, weight gain, loss, and obesity, Nestle and Nesheim sort through a great deal of the misinformation put forth by food manufacturers and diet program promoters. They elucidate the political stakes and show how federal and corporate policies have come together to create an "eat more" environment. Finally, having armed readers with the necessary information to interpret food labels, evaluate diet claims, and understand evidence as presented in popular media, the authors offer some candid advice: Get organized. Eat less. Eat better. Move more. Get political.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFood consumption. 0aFoodxCaloric content. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  abody mental health.  abooks for healthy people.  acooking.  adieting.  aeasy to read.  aeducational books.  aevaluating diets.  afood and culture books.  afood in media.  ahow many calories should i consume.  ahow to be healthier.  ahow to count calories.  ahow to gain weight.  ahow to lose weight.  ahow to stay healthy.  aimproving quality of food.  ainterpreting food labels.  aketo.  alearning from experts.  alow carb diets.  anutrition reference.  anutritional health.  aobesity.  aresearched theories.  asimple approaches.  awhat is a good body weight.1 aNesheim, Malden, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026288140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095217140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520952171423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520952171/original  a97